<TITLE> Govt to open 7 new missions </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Aug 30 (bdnews24.com)The government has decided to open missions in seven countries to find new markets for manpower. An interministerial meeting on manpower export at the Secretariat on Sunday also decided to strengthen missions in different countries. "We've decided to open diplomatic missions in seven new countries - Mauritius, Lebanon, Sudan, Greece, Botswana, Angola and Romania," finance minister A M A Muhith told reporters after the meeting. "About 65 lakh Bangladeshis are working in different countries at the moment, whose wages bolster our economy specially." Despite the ongoing global economic crunch, Bangladesh has exported 3.5 lakh workers abroad, Muhith said. "We have 31 organisations who run various professional training courses related to manpower export. Another 37 such facilities will be raised to facilitate immigrant-aspirants and augment manpower export." He said the decisions of opening new embassies and manpower training institutions will be soon implemented. "We expect that the new embassies will not only enhance manpower export, they will help diversification of export commodities and find us new markets." Commerce minister Faruq Khan, expatriates welfare and overseas employment minister Khandaker Mosharraf Hossain, foreign minister Dipu Moni, home secretary Abdus Sobhan Shikder, finance secretary Mohammed Tareque, foreign secretary Mohamed Mizarul Quayes, and labour and overseas employment secretary Ilias Ahmed also attended the meeting. bdnew
